Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels—Central banks have made only limited progress in curbing powerful global deflationary forces over most of the past decade.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero levels while conducting multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchasing operations.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank also followed the Federal Reserve's lead, each implementing their own versions of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not achieved a reasonable rise anywhere.
Although these countries are all fighting deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performance — are diverging.
The U.S. and the U.K. now have strong enough growth to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are intensifying QE, pushing policy long-term rates further into negative territory.
What is the reason for this difference?
Briefly put, it is debt.
For decades, the U.S. and the U.K. have had current account deficits and thus are debtor countries, while the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses and thus are creditor countries.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor countries but hurt creditor countries, and thus the negative rates introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated recovery in the U.S. and the U.K., but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor countries in the world — nations with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland — have experienced negative interest rates, not only on long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also on medium-term bonds.
This is definitely not a good thing.
Despite the limited effectiveness of low interest rates, the central banks of these economies continue to adhere to this policy.
If you argue that QE or lower interest rates cannot benefit the economy, they will evade the issue and counter the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — on the surface, this seems unassailable.
But in reality, this is full of loopholes.
Basic economics courses all mention this peculiar phenomenon known as the "backward-bending supply curve of savings": in certain circumstances, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because falling interest rates reduce the income of savers, they will cut back on spending, especially if they are saving for retirement.
None of these points are meant to negate the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other forms of spending.
However, the impact varies due to differences in the debt situations of the economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so whatever the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors naturally outnumber debtors.
For a country with a large amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effects of monetary policy with interest rate lower bounds differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were often small (as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, the foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly due to the leverage that led to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage continues to increase at the national level.
Although current account imbalances have eased somewhat since the onset of the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, diverging from deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, experienced large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them the main exceptions to the differentiation in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have plummeted, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export earnings sharply declined —— with many countries losing half —— forcing them into deficits, relying on the large sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
Spending cuts on a large scale are now unavoidable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
Their problem — in a sense, a luxury problem — is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall from the drop in import prices.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem to have failed to advance this goal; in fact, some external surpluses have even increased.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although the eurozone as a whole is a creditor economy, it also includes debtor countries.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are so high that the asymmetry between debtor and creditor countries continues to increase.
Most notably, since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated during this period has exceeded the total historical surplus prior to this.
Following the current trend, Germany's creditor position could increase from 60% to 100% of GDP.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to lack patience, struggling greatly with low inflation, despite the output gap gradually closing and both the U.S. and Japan achieving full employment.
Central bank governors of debtor countries must stop manipulating the economy with more monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
On the contrary, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effects of falling oil prices to fade.
European Central Bank President Draghi recently admitted that the current monetary policy stance may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same old remedy is not the solution.
